SIMPLE: multitude
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Multitude
<hw>Mul"ti*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>multitude</ets>, L. <ets>multitudo</ets>, <ets>multitudinis</ets>,
fr. <ets>multus</ets> much, many; of unknown origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A great number of persons collected together; a numerous collection
of persons; a crowd; an assembly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But when he saw the <qex>multitudes</qex>, he was moved with
compassion on them.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. ix. 36.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A great number of persons or things, regarded
collectively; <as>as, the book will be read by a <ex>multitude</ex> of
people; the <ex>multitude</ex> of stars; a <ex>multitude</ex> of
cares.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a fault in a <qex>multitude</qex> of preachers, that they
utterly neglect method in their harangues.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>multitude</qex> of flowers⟦br⟧
As countless as the stars on high.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of being many; numerousness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They came as grasshoppers for <qex>multitude</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Judg. vi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The multitude</b></col>, <cd>the populace; the mass of
men.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Throng; crowd; assembly; assemblage; commonalty;
swarm; populace; vulgar. See <er>Throng</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multitudinary</ent>⟦br⟧
